HEADWORD: Rhetoric
<hw>Rhet"o*ric</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>rh⟦eacute⟧torique</ets>, L. <ets>rhetorica</ets>, Gr. <?/<?/<?/<?/
(sc. <?/<?/<?/), fr. <?/<?/<?/ rhetorical, oratorical, fr. <?/<?/<?/
orator, rhetorician; perhaps akin to E. <ets>word</ets>; cf. <?/<?/<?/
to say.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The art of composition; especially,
elegant composition in prose.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Oratory; the art of speaking with propriety,
elegance, and force.</def> <rj><au>Locke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence, artificial eloquence; fine language or
declamation without conviction or earnest feeling.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Fig. : The power of persuasion or attraction; that
which allures or charms.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sweet, silent <qex>rhetoric</qex> of persuading eyes.</q>
<rj><qau>Daniel.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rhetorical</ent>⟦br⟧
